    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1885-05-08T23:59:59-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1885-05-08T00:00:00-05:00" n="28" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d28">
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#center">No. 28.</seg>
                </opener>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">Count <persName type="from">Kalnoky</persName> to
                                Baron <persName type="to">Schaeffer</persName>
                    </hi>.</head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#center">[Translation of telegram.]</seg>
                </opener>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Vienna</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1885-05-08">
                            <hi rend="italic">May</hi> 8,
                                1885</date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>We regret the nomination of Mr. Keiley as minister plenipotentiary and
                            envoy extraordinary to the imperial court and his sudden departure from
                            America, as here, too, like in Rome, <hi rend="italic">prevail scruples
                                against this choice.</hi>
                </p>
                <p>Please direct <hi rend="italic">in the most friendly way</hi> the
                            attention of the American Government to the generally existing
                            diplomatic practice to ask previously to any nomination of a foreign
                            minister the <hi rend="italic">agrément</hi> (consent) of the Government
                            to which he is accredited.</p>
                <p>You are therefore requested to <hi rend="italic">earnestly entreat</hi>
                            them that the newly nominated minister may not reach Vienna before our
                            confidential consent to his nomination has taken place.</p>
                <p>The position of a foreign envoy wedded to a Jewess by civil marriage
                            would be untenable and even impossible in Vienna.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>COUNT KALNOKY.</signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
